  <static seed="1454" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions1.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{m}{n}}}{{\frac{5m}{4n^{2}}}}=}</m><fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{4n}{5}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{m}{n}}}{{\frac{5m}{4n^{2}}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{m}{n}}</m> and <m>{\frac{5m}{4n^{2}}}</m>, which is <m>{4n^{2}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{m}{n}}}{{\frac{5m}{4n^{2}}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{m}{n}}\cdot{4n^{2}}}{{\frac{5m}{4n^{2}}}\cdot{4n^{2}}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{4mn}}{{5m}} \amp  \\
    \amp = {\frac{4n}{5}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Note that you are not required to enter lost domain conditions in this problem, but it<rsq/>s good to know the following.</p>
<p>Since <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> were canceled, <m>m \ne 0</m> and <m>n \ne 0</m> are in the lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
